 {"id": "franken_networkx-flowt", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] maximum_flow/minimum_cut always return float even when all capacities are int", "description": "fnx.maximum_flow / maximum_flow_value / minimum_cut / minimum_cut_value returned float values even when all edge capacities were ints. nx returns ints when inputs are integer-typed. Result: isinstance(fnx.maximum_flow_value(G, s, t), int) is False whereas nx returns True. Fix: post-process via _coerce_flow_value \u2014 if all caps are ints and result is an integer-valued float, cast to int.", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T06:31:10.983915Z", "close_reason": "Fixed in cycle-5 cycle-2: Python wrapper handles the return-type/sentinel-value divergence.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T06:31:10.983915Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T06:31:10.983915Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-edgekey", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] EdgeView __getitem__ KeyError stringifies edge key for Graph", "description": "fnx.Graph().edges[5,6] on a missing edge raised KeyError(\"(5, 6)\") (string repr of tuple) instead of KeyError((5, 6)) (original tuple). The Python-side _DiGraphEdgeView / _MultiGraphEdgeView wrappers were already correct; only the Rust-native EdgeView for simple Graph had the bug. Fixed via __getitem__ wrapper that catches KeyError and re-raises with the original edge key.", "status": "closed", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T06:42:00.007152Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T06:42:00.007152Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0, "closed_at": "2026-04-24T06:42:00.007152Z", "close_reason": "Fixed in cycle-6: _EDGE_VIEW_TYPE.__getitem__ wrapped to preserve the original edge key in KeyError args."}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-edgord", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] Graph.edges iteration canonicalizes (u, v) as (min, max) \u2014 diverges from nx insertion-preserving order", "description": "fnx.Graph.add_edge(2, 1) stores the edge internally as (1, 2); EdgeView iteration emits (1, 2) regardless of insertion order. nx preserves the original (u, v) ordering as passed to add_edge. Tests asserting `list(G.edges)[0] == (2, 1)` after add_edge(2, 1) will fail on fnx. MultiGraph is already correct \u2014 only simple Graph has this bug. Rust-side fix (internal adjacency must track insertion-order tuple, not (min, max) pair). Out of Python-layer scope.", "status": "open", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T06:42:00.007152Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T06:42:00.007152Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-vweqset", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] EdgeView Set-equality protocol broken \u2014 G.edges == {...} returns False", "description": "nx.EdgeView inherits from collections.abc.Set so `G.edges == {(0,1),(1,2)}` returns True. fnx.EdgeView is a bare Rust type with MRO [EdgeView, object] \u2014 no Set inheritance \u2014 so the same comparison returned False (the raw __eq__ returned NotImplemented and the set fallback yielded False). Fix: install Set.__eq__ / __ne__ / isdisjoint shim on _EDGE_VIEW_TYPE and set __hash__ = None. NodeView intentionally left with Mapping semantics (does NOT equal a plain node set on either fnx or nx).", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T06:50:50.986771Z", "close_reason": "Fixed: _view_set_eq/_ne/_isdisjoint methods installed on EdgeView; __hash__ nulled for protocol correctness. 5 regression tests in TestEdgeViewSetEquality.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T06:50:50.986771Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T06:50:50.986771Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}

